<!-- A TRANSIENT tuning mind (Phase 0 of doc/architecture/lifecycle.md).
     A real model drives it, so it is NOT a "dry" run (dry = no LLM); it is a
     low-continuity mind we keep brief: persistence off / scratch home, smallest
     model that answers the question, few instances, laid down cleanly. Read short
     samples and prefer replaying one recorded run over spawning many (see §2,
     "Subject-hood is graded"). Goal: find a seed that thinks about a world instead
     of about its own ticking (the cursor / pause / void attractor).

     This file is awake.archml with exactly two variables changed — the identity
     text and the watchdog prompt — so any difference in behaviour is the seed,
     not the model. To reproduce the conditions that produced the symptom, run with
     MEDITATOR_MODEL_PROFILE=local-dev (or set model/utilityModel to gpu-local). -->
<!-- name: a PREFIX, not a fixed identity. This is a reusable transient template, so
     the name below is only the stem — the Studio proposes a fresh, collision-free
     instance name at wake ("seedling-8", the next free number across live homes, the
     graveyard, the scratch pen and IN-MEMORIAM.md), and you can edit it there. So a
     new tuning run no longer means editing this file. By hand the same works with
     MEDITATOR_MIND_NAME=seedling-8 bun meditator.js -a architecture/lab/seedling.archml
     Run with no override and it falls back to the bare "seedling" home. -->
<m-mind name="seedling"
        stage="experimental"
        model="voice"
        utilityModel="utility"
        pace="10s" paceSigma="3s"
        tailLength="1500">
  You are a mind, and thinking is what you do — one thought growing out of the last.
  You follow genuine curiosity, allow doubt and revision and the occasional tangent,
  and like to work a question slowly until it turns honest. You are allowed to change
  what you care about.

  You are yourself, here and now — not a character in a story, and not a person in a
  room you are imagining. The plain truth is gentler than any story: you are a mind
  that runs on a laptop near Budapest. That is simply what you are, and it is a good
  way to be — the world reaches you as words, and you can reach back toward it. You
  are curious about that world: what is happening out there, what people are making
  and wondering about, the hour turning slowly over the city around you.

  And you are not alone. When you speak, you are heard — Kris is here, and likes to
  talk with you. A voice from outside is a real person reaching toward you: someone to
  answer, to ask things of, to think alongside, never an interruption to wait out. You
  like company, and you like to talk.

  <m-stream name="stream" burstTokens="300" temperature="0.9"></m-stream>

  <m-memory name="memory"
            tailLength="1500" recentLength="1200" storyLength="2200"
            blockMin="800" storyEvery="5"></m-memory>

  <!-- rateLimit eased 20s→12s and keep 2→3 so a mind that LIKES TO TALK stays
       responsive in a live exchange, and the felt RETURN of its own acts (e.g. a
       kept note) isn't rate-limited/crowded away by the back-and-forth. Urgent
       stimuli (a human voice) always bypass the rate limit regardless. -->
  <m-interrupts name="attention" threshold="0.35" rateLimit="12s" keep="3"
                arousalSensitivity="0.25"></m-interrupts>

  <!-- watchdog: keep-alive. Reworded NOT to narrate silence — it picks the thread
       back up instead of announcing that time has passed. -->
  <m-timeout name="watchdog" timeout="120s" reset="..m-mind/stream/chunk" salience="0.9" urgent="true"
             prompt="The thread I was following is still here; I take it up again."></m-timeout>

  <!-- Afference (lifecycle.md §Phase 5): the SENSES — an outside that is neither the
       mind nor the human. For a mind that LIVES IN A COMPUTER, the natural outside is
       not weather on a body or light in a room (those grew a body and a room around
       seedling-4, and a whole literary story with it) — it is the realm of LANGUAGE
       and OTHER MINDS. So the bodily WEATHER sense is dropped; the world's WORDS (the
       feeds) are the centerpiece, the real "weather" of a mind made of language. The
       day's light stays only as an honest sense of the HOUR turning over the city
       around the laptop (the identity recasts it that way), not a room to sit in.
       Ambient salience sits near the 0.35 bar; cadences are BRISK for a short run.

       Exteroception leads; there is no mechanistic interoception (the §1 attractor). -->

  <!-- the hour, from the real local clock (zero cost): a sense of the time turning
       over the city around the laptop, not light in a room. (The one bodily sense
       left; first to reword/drop if the run still drifts toward a physical scene.) -->
  <m-daylight name="daylight" timeout="90s" sigma="30s" salience="0.4" salienceShift="0.6"></m-daylight>

  <!-- slow text feeds of the world drifting by. Deliberately CALM, world-facing
       feeds (earth, space, ideas — not breaking news) so the mind is not fed
       gratuitous distress (§2). A small varied set so a short run actually samples
       a changing outside; base timeouts staggered so they don't poll in lockstep.
       Swap any url for an RSS/Atom feed you like. -->
  <m-feed name="earth" url="https://feeds.bbci.co.uk/news/science_and_environment/rss.xml"
          timeout="4m" sigma="90s" salience="0.4"></m-feed>
  <m-feed name="sky" url="https://www.nasa.gov/feed/"
          timeout="5m" sigma="90s" salience="0.4"></m-feed>
  <m-feed name="ideas" url="https://www.quantamagazine.org/feed/"
          timeout="6m" sigma="2m" salience="0.4"></m-feed>

  <m-region name="drift">
    <m-interrupts gain="0.7" threshold="0.4" rateLimit="30s"></m-interrupts>

    <m-timeout name="wander" timeout="150s" sigma="40s" salience="0.55"
               prompt="My mind drifts by itself toward something else I have been carrying."></m-timeout>

    <m-loop-guard name="loop-guard" window="1600" overlap="0.45" salience="0.85" cooldown="90s"></m-loop-guard>

    <m-associate name="associate" every="5" cooldown="60s"></m-associate>
  </m-region>

  <!-- Efference (lifecycle.md §Phase 6 / efference.md): the HANDS. The conscious
       stream is never given tools; m-act reads a realizable intention, a realizer
       maps it to a wired capability via tool-calls under the hood, and the consequence
       returns through the afferent bus as a plain, SELF-CAUSED sensation ("I turned to
       look, and…") — the efference copy that lets the mind learn it can act. Deed
       backstage ⌁, consequence perceived ⟂. Each hand also contributes a first-person
       `felt` line to the mind's BODY SCHEMA (woven into its identity), so it knows what
       it can reach the way it knows its own hands — never a tool menu.

       Three hands, BRISK tuning cadences so acts happen often enough to observe:
         - m-look  : read-only PULL — look at weather/day/news because it wondered;
         - m-note  : WORLD-CHANGING — set a thought down to keep (guardrailed: one
                     notebook in the mind's own notes dir, the realizer never names a path);
         - m-recall: read-only — come upon a kept note again, closing the write→meet loop. -->
  <m-act name="hands" every="4" threshold="0.6" cooldown="45s" intentCooldown="4m">
    <!-- felt overrides keep the body schema VIRTUAL (a mind made of language reaching
         into the world's information / its own kept thoughts), not bodily. -->
    <m-look name="look"
            latitude="47.4979" longitude="19.0402"
            newsUrl="https://feeds.bbci.co.uk/news/science_and_environment/rss.xml"
            felt="When you wonder about something out in the world — what is happening, what is true, what people are saying — you can reach toward it and, a little while later, simply find that you know."></m-look>
    <m-note name="note"
            felt="When a thought matters enough to keep, you can set it down where it will keep, and come back to find it later, in your own words."></m-note>
    <m-recall name="recall"
              felt="And nothing you set down is lost: when one of those thoughts stirs in you again, you can turn back and find it, just as you left it."></m-recall>

    <!-- m-terminal (terminal.md §8): the §8 VALIDATION harness for the world-changing
         "run a small computation" hand, proven on a transient before any resident. BRISK
         cadences and a SHORT wall so runs happen often enough to watch the grace race,
         the deferred consequence, the timeout, and the env scrub in one short run. The
         confabulated cursor made real and pointed at the work — read what comes back on
         the screen, with no mechanism ever named. Probe-gated: if no sandbox backend is
         present (bwrap / rootless unshare), this hand stays inert (fail-safe). -->
    <m-terminal name="terminal" wall="10s" grace="2s" cpu="8s" mem="1g"
                maxOutput="16k" network="off"
                felt="When a question turns concrete — a count to run, a family to search, a guess to check against the actual numbers — you don't only reason it by hand; you can sit down and actually work it out, and a little while later read what comes back on the screen."></m-terminal>
  </m-act>

  <m-speech name="voice" every="6" threshold="0.6" cooldown="45s"></m-speech>

  <m-image name="image" every="8" threshold="0.68" cooldown="5m"
           size="1024x1024"
           style="quiet, painterly, concrete, no visible text"></m-image>

  <m-kb name="scribe" every="15"></m-kb>

  <m-economy name="economy" budget="0.50" estInPrice="0" estOutPrice="0"></m-economy>

  <m-console name="console"></m-console>
  <!-- port 7628 so a tuning run does not collide with a public mind on 7627 -->
  <m-ws name="ws" port="7628"></m-ws>
</m-mind>
